The world is not (always) linear


Probability

Probability

  • Probability theory is of practical value and intuitive meaning in connection with real or conceptual experiments (Feller 1950). The formal quantification of uncertainty.
  • Uncertainty comes into the picture when we start doing statistical inference: what can we infer about a population parameter given sample statistics?
  • Relative Frequency or Frequentist Approach: the probability of a particular outcome is the proportion of times that outcome would occur in a long run of repeated observations.

Bernoulli distribution

Probability

  • Coin toss. Dice rolls. Playing roulette. Selecting a random sample of people and observing people with different attributes. Election outcomes.
  • Coin flips are independent. The outcome of Flip 1 has no effect on the outcome of Flip 2.
  • The binomial distribution (the sum of independent and identically distributed Bernoulli random variables) does not dictate the outcome of any given coin flip.
  • Law of large numbers.
  • Two types of variation: variance of the sample data, Y; variance of a sample statistic (eg the mean of Y) across repeated sampling (captured by the sampling distribution).

Probability

We can replicate a coin toss in \(R\) with the code:


rbinom(1, 1, .5)

Sampling variation

  • Flip a coin 4 times, compute a summary statistic (eg proportion of heads in 4 flips), repeat.
  • The standard deviation of a sampling distribution goes by a special name: the standard error.
  • It is an estimate of the dispersion of the sampling distribution.
  • Sampling error/variability decreases as sample size increases.

The binomial distribution



The world is still not simple

(Un)fortunately, the world is not a series of coin flips


  • With coin flips, we know the underlying distribution. For most interesting problems, we do not.
  • Not every outcome has a binary set of outcomes (what if there are five outcomes?).
  • We have some help, though. The law of large numbers, the central limits theorem.

Using logistic regression to estimate outcomes

Logistic regression


\(Pr(y = 1) = logit^{1}(x_i\beta)\)
